Being a fat content creator can be hard! 🥴🙃 swipe through and please share what resonates! (I left the last one blank so you can add your own experiences!)💕🙏🏻

Even with all the “progress” we’ve seen in size-inclusive fashion and body-positive marketing, fat content creators are often still treated as second class citizens compared to their thin counterparts. I can’t even count all the times I’ve been left off the list of local influencer events that my thin colleagues get invited to. Or how often I’m told by brands that don’t have a budget for paid partnerships when I know they’re paying thin creators. Or how often I’m hired by a brand that says my audience  demographic is a great fit but when I look at their socials, there are no fat people in sight! And don’t even get me started on brands who preach body positivity and size inclusivity but don’t actually carry a size larger that XXL or 20!

Now that hating yourself is out of style and embracing your body is trendy companies want to cash in but don’t want to put their money where their mouth is. And that’s honestly worse than the companies who still pretend like fat people don’t exist, because profiting from the labor of fat people and access to our audiences without actually serving the fat community is exploitative and simply unethical. 

Here’s how you can help:

If you’re a supporter, leave comments on brands social media posts and send DMs to brands telling them that you’d like to see more inclusive body representation!

If you’re a thin content creator, look around the next time you’re at an event or working on a brand campaign and notice when your fat colleagues are excluded. Recommend your fat counterparts to brands and PR companies you have relationships with and let them know you support size inclusivity!

Y’all I was SO NERVOUS 😬 🤣

I’ve been wanting to try @zaruba__art @paintyournoodz class for a long time and I finally decided to sign up and go for it! I had no idea how hard it would be for me! I consider myself a champion of body positivity and I feel like I’ve got a pretty good handle on my own positive body image…but I’ll be honest, I felt very critical of my body at the beginning of this process. 

The first step is taking a reference photo and I absolutely agonized over choosing one to paint! The idea of immortalizing my pose in a painting just felt so permanent! Then when the class started I found myself looking around at the other participants canvases and comparing my body to theirs. Then there was the added pressure of painting! Even with an incredibly talented instructor, I struggled to trust the process and just allow myself to be a beginner. As a professional creative, I am extremely hard on myself and always pushing for excellence. Even though I know art can exist purely for self expression, this was a tough exercise for me.

BUT I did it! And I’m super proud of myself! I’m proud of myself for pushing past my comfort zone in so many ways and for proving to myself that I’m capable of trying something new, not being the best, and still having fun and feeling accomplished! Will’s reaction was also so affirming because he thinks I’m beautiful as I am and is always proud of my creative pursuits. 🥰💖

I’ve been looking at this painting of my body every day since last weekend and each day I love what I see more and more! This experience was such a great reminder for myself that growth is never linear and I will continue to have breakthroughs in my self acceptance journey. I’m so grateful to now view my body through a less critical lens and be able to see body as a work of art! 💕💕💕

“What if I told you none of it was accidental…”💫✨💕

Whenever times are hard and my dreams seem far from reach, I’m reminded of that little girl I used to be. The one who was relentlessly bullied for her weight, who people told “you have a pretty face”, and who day dreamed every day about becoming a big star and proving to everyone who ever doubted my worth that I was special. 

Now I chase those dreams for HER. The bullies, the nay sayers, the internet trolls…none of them matter. She is my “why”. I believe in her day dream and I will work endlessly to shine her light on the world like the bright star she is! 

The end of the year is always a tough time for me mentally. My birthday is in February, so not only am I critical of what what I have or haven’t accomplished over the course of the year, I’m also fearful that the clock is ticking. I know it’s silly to think this way because there’s no deadline for success and growth isn’t linear. So I made this post as a reminder for myself that it’s okay to want more, but it’s important to appreciate what I have. I think little me would be proud of my achievements and even more amazed at my resilience and commitment. 💖💕

“I wish I had your confidence” is one of the most common comments I get online. I have great news! You absolutely CAN have my confidence! Here’s how:

1. I decided I was worthy. My life began improving when I realized that self blame and pity isn’t the same thing as accountability and I’m in charge of my self image and my own happiness. I wasn’t sure how I was going to become the confident version of myself I envisioned but I decided I was worthy of being that woman. 

2. Curate your community online & IRL. Follow accounts on social media that reflect your values & interests. Unfollow anyone you constantly compare yourself to or who makes you feel inferior The comparison game is a losing one! Surround yourself with people who uplift you and pay attention to who you feel safe & comfy around. It’s important that the people in your life encourage you to be your best but also accept you for who you are today! 

3. Do those cheesy things people recommend that sound dumb, even if you feel silly. Find positive affirmations online, write them down, repeat them in the mirror each day. Make a list of 3 things you like about yourself and 3 things you’re grateful for every night before bed. Write down your fears & doubts on paper and tear them up or burn them. The way you speak to yourself out loud AND in your head is super important for your self esteem and you have to take control of the narrative. 

4. My final tip for confidence is: fake it. We’ve all heard the advice “fake it til you make it” and that might sound like you’re being encouraged to lie but really it’s just dress rehearsal! Practice makes progress and when you start seeing “faking it” as rehearsal for your dream life, you’ll find that over time you slowly become that person! 

I’ve also had a looot of success with goal setting and manifestation! Let me know if you’d like to hear more about that! Feel free to leave questions in the comments or send me a DM! Working on yourself is one of the hardest things you’ll ever do but it’s the the best investment you can make. 💖🙏🏻✨

🙄 Welcome to January, where everywhere you turn someone is trying to sell you something for “unwanted belly fat” or “your dream body”. 

My body is not an unwanted nightmare to me. There’s no right or wrong way to exist in a body. Health and beauty has no one size or shape. The pursuit of wellness should be about how you feel inside and out, not what size jeans you wear. 

This time of year is a brutal reminder that not only do so many people fear looking like me, they are willing to take drastic measures to prevent it from happening. They’re willing to deprive their bodies of food, risk injuries doing extreme exercise, take unnecessary medications, and even have elective surgery…and then have the audacity to call it self improvement. 

Some will say “don’t take it personally” but I’m a person. Fat people are real people with real feelings. How am I supposed to feel when I see people dedicating their entire yearly goal to looking less like me? And this is just my opinion, but most people would be better served trying to be more like me. Maybe at the end of 2023 you’ll be thinner but will you be kind, successful, loved, and comfortable in your own skin? Will you even be healthier or prettier or just…thinner? 

Before you give in to the lie that the only way to live a full and happy life is to be thin, ask yourself what areas of your life actually need improvement. Or you could end up broke, tired, hungry, and still not satisfied with yourself. 

When I start blaming the way I look for my problems, I choose to dig deeper. I can’t control how others feel about my body, but I shouldn’t have to alter my natural form to conform to someone else’s definition of beauty, health, or success. I don’t exist to make other people rich or comfortable. So I’ll spend my time and money on things that will actually help me grown as a person and achieve my goals, like investing in my career, nurturing my relationship with myself, making time for self care, and making memories through experiences and quality time with loved ones. 💕✨

January is always full of fatphobic ads for weight loss products and toxic diet culture is always a little louder this time of year. There is no ailment or disease that affects fat people exclusively. Causation and correlation aren’t the same thing, yet our fatphobic society insists on blaming fatness and labeling fat bodies as an epidemic. Meanwhile, the long-term negative mental and physical effects of intentional weight loss are ignored. 

I was a healthy child with a naturally slow metabolism. Fatphobia perpetuated by doctors, teachers, peers, and the media led me to develop an e*ting disorder that plagued my mental and physical health for 13 years. But fatphobia is the root cause of my ED, which led to  anxiety and life-threatening depression. 

I’ve been in recovery for 5 years. Though I live in a fat body, I’m healthier now than ever before. And more importantly, I’m happier, and capable of living my life fully and unapologetically. Health is subjective and fleeting. @bluelagoonis is one of the most popular destinations for Iceland tourists, and for good reason! It’s an incredible experience but one that is very unique and requires some planning ahead.

Here are 5 tips for visiting Blue Lagoon:

1. Book in advance! This place is POPULAR and will likely sell out even on weekdays and in the off season! 

2. It’s possible that your American debit/credit card won’t work on the Blue Lagoon website. If so you can book over the phone (plan for the time difference) or via third party. 

3. The water has a high concentration of silica, which is great for your skin but can seriously dry out your hair. It won’t cause permanent damage, but can leave your hair dry and unmanageable for days. Blue Lagoon provides conditioner in the locker rooms and strongly recommends applying it generously to your hair and leaving it in prior to entering the water. I took this to heart and slathered that conditioner before and after swimming like my life depended on it! My hair was back to normal after two washes. 

4. You’re probably gonna be nude in front of strangers. If this makes you uncomfortable, plan accordingly! There’s a pretty strict protocol for preparing to enter the lagoon and washing your body and hair is non-negotiable. The showers have glass privacy doors but they don’t lock. If you’re uncomfortable being in your birthday suit in front of others, I recommend wearing your suit underneath your clothes so that you walk to the showers in your suit and remove it inside the shower behind the privacy glass. 

5. They have dining options on site but while re-entry is permitted, it’s not encouraged. If you want to take a break from swimming to eat, you’ll need to go through the locker rooms and a one-way exit at the front desk. To re-enter an employee has to let you in through the exit rather than the entrance (because it’s always so busy) then you’ll have to shower in the locker rooms again. It’s annoying & complicated so I recommend eating before hand!

✨💫 Being “delusional” is my favorite life hack because it’s actually rooted in fact, and once you master the art of Delulu, you hold all the power! Okay hear me out, because it’s really simple (not always easy, but simple!):

✨Every human has insecurities because feeling insecure is a natural human emotion. Think of the person you consider to be the epitome of beauty…they absolutely have bad body image days like you do! Everyone poops, right? Same concept here.

✨You will be criticized no matter what you look like. By strangers, haters, society, etc. you’re damned if ya do and you’re damned if ya don’t! It’s literally impossible to impress and appease every single person and someone out there will always have something negative to say. So there’s really no use is driving yourself crazy trying to be perfect or hating yourself for having “flaws”. You have better things to do.

✨The rules aren’t real. Society’s beauty standards are made up by a bunch of dudes. Ew. Being “delusional” can’t protect you from being discriminated against because of your body. But it can help protect your heart from internalizing that shit. Just because the world can be evil doesn’t mean you have to let that evil live inside of you! You can feel hurt, grieve, get angry, feel all the feelings! But you don’t have to subscribe to any of it because it’s not your truth! No one is allowed to tell you how to feel about YOURSELF! 

There you have it. The foundation of delusional thinking! You’re hot and awesome because why? Because YOU say so! Full stop! 

💕Bonus Round💕
“Loving your body” doesn’t mean you never feel insecure or have rough body image days. It just means you treat yourself with love! You look in the mirror and say “ugh gross,” (cuz you’re only human!) but then you’re like, “wait, no ma’am, we don’t talk like that on Barbie.com!” And you buy yourself a Starbucks latte because you’re a brave girl who deserves a treat! 💅🏻🥰💖

🩵💜Today, September 10th, is World Suicide Prevention Day and the first day of National Suicide Prevention Week. Swipe through to learn about the warning signs & risk factors and how to start a helpful conversation.

I’ve struggled with my mental health since childhood and experienced suicidal thoughts for the first time at only 12 years old. I’ve been through two life saving hospitalizations, one at 17 and another at 24. Though I’ve made huge strides in my mental health recovery, my medical history means I’m more susceptible to depression and suicidal ideation when navigating life’s challenges. Awareness of the risks, warning signs, and how to talk about my mental health are preventative measures that have saved my life many times over.

According to the World Health Organization: 

More than 700,000 people die by suicide every year. 

For each suicide, there are likely more than 20 suicide attempts.

Suicide was the fourth leading cause of death among 15–29-year-olds globally in 2019.

Talking about mental health can be difficult, but having these tough conversations is the key to suicide prevention. I haven’t posted in 2 months and I’ve barely touched my phone or looked at social media since October. People have reached out to see if I’m okay and I can’t even express how much that means to me ( I promise to respond soon). The truth is: I’m not okay. I’m very sick and it’s turned my life upside down in every way imaginable. I finally feel ready to start posting again and want to share what I’ve been going through.

Fibromyalgia is a neurological disease that is under-researched and misunderstood. My symptoms began shortly after my divorce in 2017 and I was finally diagnosed in August 2023. Without an accurate diagnosis, I’ve been unknowingly triggering flare ups for the past 6 years, leading to subsequent complications including a sleep disorder, spinal stenosis, chronic migraines, anxiety, and depression resulting in a vicious cycle. 

On a good day: My pain is bearable (mostly), I can hold a conversation but not for too long, I can complete a few tasks but most will be left undone, I move slowly, and require naps. The more “faking it” I have to do, the more I’ll pay for later.

On a bad day: The pain is so overwhelming that I’m irritable, anxious, paranoid, and sometimes all I can do is cry. I can’t walk further than about 250ft without rest, my balance is wobbly, and I have tremors. My fatigue is all consuming and I drift in and out of sleep while never getting true rest because my pain wakes me up. I can’t drive myself anywhere, I need a chair to shower, and I’m so weak/sensitive that even my clothes feel heavy. Simple tasks like brushing my teeth or eating are difficult and exhausting. 

My migraine med has worked well, so thankfully I’m not having migraines multiple times a week (just when it rains). I’m also taking an antidepressant to help with pain but it’s not working. Thankfully, my doctors and I are discussing treatment options that are more unconventional/experimental, which is giving me some hope.

.I deeply appreciate your support and I’m looking forward to more good days and healing in 2024.

WHEW 😅 2023 was a rough year for actors, agents, and the film industry as a whole! An acting career isn’t for the faint of heart and it’s easy to feel discouraged. As I reflect on 2023’s obstacles and challenges, I’m choosing to celebrate wins of every size!

This business is tough to begin with. But TWO union strikes?! Writers Guild of America strike lasted 148 days (5/2-9/27) and the Screen Actors Guild - American Federation of Television and Radio Artists strike lasted 118 days (7/14-11/8). That’s 190 days of striking, followed by the holidays which are notoriously slow for film/TV work. Needless to say, opportunities were sparse this year. Standing in solidarity with WGA and SAG-AFTRA was a no-brainer and I’m immensely grateful for the union leaders and members who fought for all actors and writers. 

On top of this, my health took a nosedive and I was diagnosed with fibromyalgia in August. The widespread pain and overwhelming fatigue caused by this neurological disease prevented me  from networking, collaborating, studying, and creating original content, all vital elements to building an acting career. I had to leave my beloved acting studio, unfinished screenplays and sketches collected metaphorical dust, and I became increasingly isolated from the Nashville film community. 

In the face of these setbacks, I made difficult sacrifices in other areas of my life and mustered the strength to submit for every audition I received from my agent, accept every booking, and make a short film entirely on my own for the Nashville 48 Hour Film Project resulting in 2 screenings, 4 nominations, and awards for Best Actress and Audience Choice. I’m deeply grateful for the hard work and guidance of @mccrayagency and to @nashville48hfp for fostering creativity and community among Nashville filmmakers of all skill levels. 

I believe every audition request, callback, booking, and accolade of 2023 is confirmation that I’m walking in my purpose and this passion was planted within me for a reason. I’m manifesting a booked and busy 2024, full of professional growth, creative collaboration, and artistic expression! 🎬💕

✨it’s okay to unfollow people on social media if their posts are upsetting to you or just don’t resonate anymore. Leave quietly and let them do their thing while doing what’s best for yourself.
✨Everyone deserves to feel good about themselves. Full stop. Doesn’t matter what they look like or how healthy they are: being happy in your own skin is a GOOD THING. Not to mention, people take better care of themselves when they feel good about themselves. 
✨People of all sizes and health statuses deserve to be treated with respect and dignity. This should be common sense!
